dict.string: Archives a webpage using the Wayback Machine
No URL passed, or could not read URL from an open browser
The archived page has been copied to your clipboard
Saves a snapshot on the Wayback Machine
The page could not be reached for archiving

file_path="$HOME/Library/Application Support/Alfred/Workflow Data/com.joshua.shew.archive.page/log.txt"
line_cutoff=100
if [[ -f "$file_path" ]]; then # head to read; then mv to overwrite head -n "$line_cutoff" "$file_path" > "${file_path}.tmp" && mv "${file_path}.tmp" "$file_path" fi

file_path="$HOME/Library/Application Support/Alfred/Workflow Data/com.joshua.shew.archive.page/execution_count.txt"
execution_count=0
if [[ -f "$file_path" ]]; then first_line=$(head -n 1 "$file_path") if [[ "$first_line" =~ ^[0-9]+$ ]]; then execution_count=$first_line fi fi
((execution_count++))
echo $execution_count > "$file_path"
echo $execution_count

## Usage
Archives the frontmost browser tab using Internet Archive's Wayback Machine. Alternatively, you can pass in a URL as an argument, or perform the action from Alfred clipboard history with the Universal Action.
- <kbd>︎</kbd> Archive and copy the archive URL to clipboard. - <kbd></kbd><kbd>︎</kbd> Open the Wayback Machine website for archiving. No automatic copy to clipboard. - <kbd></kbd><kbd>︎</kbd> Copy the resulting URL in markdown format: `[archive](<URL>)`
